Name.BusinessNameLine1: EAST COAST MIGRANT HEAD START PROJECT

IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDescription: Our mission is to prepare young children for educational success - especially the children of migrant and seasonal farmworkers - by providing holistic, high quality early childhood services for families in a nurturing, culturally sensitive environment
IRS990.MissionDescription: Our mission is to prepare young children for educational success - especially the children of migrant and seasonal farmworkers - by providing holistic, high quality early childhood services for families in a nurturing, culturally sensitive environment
IRS990.Description: Migrant Head Start Services - The agency served 4,867 children in various states from New Jersey to Florida. Services are provided directly in North Carolina, Alabama and Florida and delegated to sub recipients in other states. Services include Early Childhood Development, medical/dental exams and treatment, healthy meals, mental health observations. Parent involvement is critical to the operation of the program which operates during the local agricultural seasons.

Activity2.Description: Provide for expansion of Migrant Head start services to 55 additional children. This includes two separate site development projects to provide space for center based services. These sites are in Bladen, NC and Indiantown, FL. Funding was received from a one-time expansion grant from the Department of Health and HumanServices, Administration for Children and Families, Head Start Bureau. Bladen, NC operations for expansion started in May, 2010 and Indiantown, FL will commence in November, 2010.

Activity3.Description: Provide training and technical assistance to subcontractors and staff of East Coast Migrant Head Start Project(ECMHSP). Objective of the program is to ensure the quality and compliance of all operations within the pervue of ECMHSP. This is accomplished through on site training and technical assistance, cluster training, and annual conference activities. Staff are supported in professional development activities to ensure the agency is in compliance with all statutes and regulations related to teacher credentialing.

Form990ScheduleIPartIV.Identifier: Grantmaker's Description of How Grants are Used
Form990ScheduleIPartIV.Explanation: East Coast Migrant Head Start mainains records that comply with all grant rquirments and GAAP. The agency's management takes an active role in monitoring the expenditure of all grant funds on a regular monthly basis. Internal controls exist that limit the risk of error or fraud. Audits have shown no deficiencies in financial management of the organization.

GeneralExplanation.ReturnReference: Form 990, Part VI, Line 19: Other Organization Documents Publicly Available
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: All documents are available to the public upon request. All documents are provided to funding sources as requested on an annual basis and are posted on the Head Start Enterprise System Website.

GeneralExplanation.ReturnReference: Form 990, Part VI, Line 15b: Compensation Review and Approval Process for Officers and Key Employees
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: Compensation of the CEO is determined using information provided by an independent compensation consultant and approved by the Board of Directors. The organization has a written employemnt contract with the CEO.

GeneralExplanation.ReturnReference: Form 990, Part VI, Line 12c: Explanation of Monitoring and Enforcement of Conflicts
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: Through review of transactions that could present a potential conflict of interest.

GeneralExplanation.ReturnReference: Form 990, Part VI, Line 11: Form 990 Review Process
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: The 990 is reviewed by the Director of Finance for consistancy with the audited financial statements. After that review a draft of the 990 is provided to the board of directors for their feedback before filing.

GeneralExplanation.ReturnReference: Form 990, Part III, Line 3: Ceased Conducting or Significant Changes To Services
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: The Migrant Education Even Start Program grant ended in 2009. This program / grant was related to developing and providing literacy services to Migrant Farmworker families.
